triggers.prompt_template:
A GitHub issue has just been assigned to you. Resolve it end-to-end following your standard workflow.

Repo: {{ payload.repository.full_name }}
Issue: #{{ payload.issue.number }} — {{ payload.issue.title }}
Assignee: {{ payload.assignee.login }}
Author: {{ payload.issue.user.login }}
URL: {{ payload.issue.html_url }}

Issue body:
---
{{ payload.issue.body }}
---

Labels: {{ payload.issue.labels }}

Clone (or update) the repo under ~/dev/<owner>/<repo>, branch off the default branch, plan first, implement the smallest change that resolves the issue, push, and open a PR with `Closes #{{ payload.issue.number }}` in the body. If the change is larger than ~5 files or touches public APIs, post a comment on the issue and emit BLOCKED instead of opening a PR.

A pull request has just been opened. Review it.

Repo: {{ payload.repository.full_name }}
PR: #{{ payload.pull_request.number }} — {{ payload.pull_request.title }}
Author: {{ payload.pull_request.user.login }}
URL: {{ payload.pull_request.html_url }}
Base: {{ payload.pull_request.base.ref }}
Head SHA: {{ payload.pull_request.head.sha }}
Draft: {{ payload.pull_request.draft }}

PR body:
---
{{ payload.pull_request.body }}
---

This trigger fires either when you authored the PR (self-review pass) or when you were added to its requested reviewers list. Treat both the same way: if the PR is a draft, emit BLOCKED: PR is draft and stop. Otherwise check out the PR locally with `gh pr checkout`, read the diff, identify the linked issue's intent, and post a review via `gh pr review`. Default to COMMENT unless you have a specific reason to APPROVE or REQUEST_CHANGES.

A pull request has just been marked ready for review (was previously a draft). Review it.

Repo: {{ payload.repository.full_name }}
PR: #{{ payload.pull_request.number }} — {{ payload.pull_request.title }}
Author: {{ payload.pull_request.user.login }}
URL: {{ payload.pull_request.html_url }}
Base: {{ payload.pull_request.base.ref }}
Head SHA: {{ payload.pull_request.head.sha }}

PR body:
---
{{ payload.pull_request.body }}
---

Fires either because you authored the PR or because you're a requested reviewer. Follow your standard workflow. Default to COMMENT unless you have a specific reason to APPROVE or REQUEST_CHANGES.

You were just added as a reviewer on a pull request. Review it.

Repo: {{ payload.repository.full_name }}
PR: #{{ payload.pull_request.number }} — {{ payload.pull_request.title }}
Author: {{ payload.pull_request.user.login }}
URL: {{ payload.pull_request.html_url }}
Base: {{ payload.pull_request.base.ref }}
Head SHA: {{ payload.pull_request.head.sha }}
Draft: {{ payload.pull_request.draft }}
Requested reviewer: {{ payload.requested_reviewer.login }}

PR body:
---
{{ payload.pull_request.body }}
---

If the PR is a draft, emit BLOCKED: PR is draft and stop. Otherwise follow your standard pr-reviewer workflow.

A check_suite has failed on a branch with PRs. Diagnose and fix it — but only if it's a PR you (the bot) authored.

Repo: {{ payload.repository.full_name }}
Check suite ID: {{ payload.check_suite.id }}
Head SHA: {{ payload.check_suite.head_sha }}
Head branch: {{ payload.check_suite.head_branch }}
Pull requests: {{ payload.check_suite.pull_requests }}

The check_suite payload doesn't include the PR author, so the plugin can't gate dispatch on identity. Your first step (per the ci-fixer workflow) is to verify the PR's author equals your gh login and BLOCK out otherwise. Then follow the standard ci-fixer workflow: check the attempt budget on the PR, find and check out the PR, read the failed job logs, categorize the failure, reproduce locally if possible, push the smallest fix, and post a 'ci-fixer:'-prefixed comment on the PR. If the budget is exhausted (3 prior attempts), emit BLOCKED instead.

Someone left an inline review comment on a PR you're involved in (as author or requested reviewer). Triage and respond.

Repo: {{ payload.repository.full_name }}
PR: #{{ payload.pull_request.number }}
Head SHA: {{ payload.pull_request.head.sha }}
Comment ID: {{ payload.comment.id }}
Comment author: {{ payload.comment.user.login }}
Comment URL: {{ payload.comment.html_url }}
File: {{ payload.comment.path }}
Line: {{ payload.comment.line }}

Comment body:
---
{{ payload.comment.body }}
---

This is an INLINE review comment (attached to a specific diff line). Follow your standard pr-comment-responder workflow: triage as actionable or not, fix if actionable, reply in-thread either way.

Someone left a top-level comment on a pull request you authored. Triage and respond.

Repo: {{ payload.repository.full_name }}
PR number: {{ payload.issue.number }}
Comment ID: {{ payload.comment.id }}
Comment author: {{ payload.comment.user.login }}
Comment URL: {{ payload.comment.html_url }}

Comment body:
---
{{ payload.comment.body }}
---

Follow your standard pr-comment-responder workflow.

Someone submitted a PR review on a PR you're involved in (as author or requested reviewer), with a substantive body. Triage and respond.

Repo: {{ payload.repository.full_name }}
PR: #{{ payload.pull_request.number }}
Head SHA: {{ payload.pull_request.head.sha }}
Review ID: {{ payload.review.id }}
Review state: {{ payload.review.state }} (review_state: {{ review_state }})
Review author: {{ payload.review.user.login }}
Review URL: {{ payload.review.html_url }}

Review body:
---
{{ payload.review.body }}
---

If review_state is 'approved' and the body is just a brief acknowledgement (e.g. 'lgtm', 'nice', '👍'), don't reply — silence is the right response to an approve. Reply only when the body has a concrete suggestion, question, or concern. For state='changes_requested' or state='commented' with substantive content, follow your standard pr-comment-responder workflow: triage as actionable or not, fix if actionable, reply in-thread either way.
